<subSubSection box="[199,457,1440,1467]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="71.[151,1437,1260,1682]" box="[199,457,1440,1467]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,324,1441,1467]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Host plant</emphasis>
. Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="71.[151,1437,1260,1682]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1477,1503]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Remarks</emphasis>
. This is a large and light-colored species, so far known only from Primorskij Kraj and 
<collectingCountry box="[1317,1389,1477,1503]" name="South Korea" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Korea</collectingCountry>
. No molecular data are available. 
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A." box="[480,689,1512,1538]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="359 - 438" refId="ref76809" refString="Shinohara, A. (2002 b) Systematics of the leaf-rolling or webspinning sawfly subfamily Pamphiliinae: a preliminary overview. In: Viitasaari, M. (Ed.), Sawflies (Hymenoptera, Symphyta) I. Tremex Press, Helsinki, pp. 359 - 438." type="book chapter" year="2002">Shinohara (2002b)</bibRefCitation>
placed it in his 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Kontuniemi" authorityYear="1958" box="[867,1022,1512,1538]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevicornis">
<emphasis box="[867,1022,1512,1538]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">P. brevicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgroup of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1812" box="[1170,1270,1512,1538]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="histrio">
<emphasis box="[1170,1270,1512,1538]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">P. histrio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="71.[151,1437,1260,1682]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<bibRefCitation author="Lee, J. - W. &amp; Choi, J. - K. &amp; Park, B." box="[199,386,1548,1575]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 96" refId="ref74711" refString="Lee, J. - W., Choi, J. - K. &amp; Park, B. (2019) Synoptic list of Symphyta (Hymenoptera) in Korea. Journal of Species Research, 8, 1 - 96." type="journal article" year="2019">
Lee 
<emphasis box="[248,304,1548,1574]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">et al.</emphasis>
(2019)
</bibRefCitation>
gave 
<taxonomicName box="[452,583,1548,1575]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Salicaceae" genus="Populus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[452,544,1548,1574]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Populus</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
as a host of this species without showing source of information. This record may have been based on Shinohara’s (1995) statement, “the 
<typeStatus box="[823,921,1584,1610]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">holotype</typeStatus>
female was found crawling on a leaf of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Salicaceae" genus="Populus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Populus</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
(probably 
<taxonomicName box="[347,487,1620,1646]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Salicaceae" genus="Populus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="davidiana">
<emphasis box="[347,487,1620,1646]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">P. davidiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), which may be the host plant.” Obviously, this statement was not a host record and the host is still unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
